11. Note on Historical Attributions and Oral
Traditions (with reference to Gulzar-e-Jalaliya)
It is further observed that numerous elders and a substantial number of narratives have,
over time, become incorporated into the family tradition through both oral and written
transmission, despite in reality belonging to other Sadat lineages. In many instances, such
elders, their associated accounts, and the shrines attributed to them either belonged to the
maternal lineage of the ancestors, or were figures venerated within regions inhabited by
Sadat communities, where, owing to the presence of shrines of Sadat saints, local
populations began to regard them as their own forefathers. In this context, it is also
correctly noted in Gulzar-e-Jalaliya that many families tend to exaggerate their lineage
and ancestral prestige, at times even incorporating elements of embellished or unfounded
glorification, which subsequently gives rise to contradictions and conflicts in later
generations. Accordingly, the mosques referenced in such narratives were either associated
with the maternal ancestry who themselves belonged to established Sadat families or were
attributed collectively by regionally settled Sadat communities who, on the basis of shared
