It is observed that within the genealogical narratives recorded in Gulzar-e-Jalaliya,
considerable emphasis has been placed on the presence of ancestral mosques, shrines, and
spiritual centers attributed to the forefathers of this lineage in “Hind,” as well as in
locations such as Agra and Firozabad. These accounts appear prominently within family
narratives and reflect the importance of spiritual heritage associated with the ancestors.
However, it is essential to contextualize these statements within their historical and
linguistic framework. In earlier periods, the term “Hind” was broadly used to denote the
entire Indian subcontinent, which included regions that are today part of modern-day
Pakistan. Within family oral traditions, this term continued to be used generically, often
without precise geographical distinction. As a result, locations remembered as being in
“Hind” or associated with cities such as Agra or Firozabad may, upon closer historical and
geographical examination, correspond instead to regions within present-day Punjab and
Sindh.
Based on available research and surviving evidence, it appears more likely that many of
the ancestral religious sites including mosques, burial places, and spiritual centers
attributed to the forefathers were situated in areas such as Lahore, Multan, and parts of
Sindh. These regions historically served as major centers of Sadat settlement and religious
activity, and continue to contain numerous shrines and graves consistent with the family’s
lineage traditions.
Furthermore, certain narratives within the family appear to have incorporated elements
derived from maternal or extended familial associations. For example, references linking
Syed Shakir Ali directly to a shrine in Firozabad may not correspond to his own burial or
direct ancestral site, but rather to a shrine associated with relatives from the maternal side.
